    <text type="letter"> 
        <body> 
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="loc.02216.001.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener>  
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place"><handShift rend="printed"/>The Critic</name>
                    <name type="place">52 &amp; 54 Lafayette Place</name>
                    <name type="place">New York</name>
                    <name type="place"><handShift rend="manuscript"/>"Bellevue"</name>
                    <name type="place">Bordentown, N. J.</name>
                    <date when="1890-06-13">13 June 1890</date>
                </dateline>
                <salute>Dear W. Whitman:</salute> 
            </opener>
            <p>Nearly a month ago I sent you a request to vote<ptr target="n5002d"/> (as a member of <hi rend="underline"
                    >The Critic's</hi><ptr target="loc.02216_n1"/> Academy of Forty Immortals) for nine successors to the
                members deceased since our leaders elected the Forty in 1884. I sent a list of about
                65 unsuccessful candidates (or rather nominees) who were voted for at that time, &#38;
                asked you to pick out nine of them or to name nine others if you preferred. Nearly
                    all<pb xml:id="leaf001v" facs="loc.02216.002.jpg" type="verso"/> the
                "Academicians" have sent in their votes; but I don't want to announce the result of
                the thing till I hear from you. <hi rend="underline">If you have lost the printed
                    slip, I can send you another.</hi> We shall not tell how any individual voted,
                but only how they all voted&#8212;the net result. I hope you'll not disappoint
                us.<ptr target="loc.02216_n2"/></p>
            <closer>
                <salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>
                <signed>J. B. Gilder</signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
